body:
add the --build_wheel option when calling build.bat to build a python wheel.
you can install the resulting python whl that gets built.

alternatively, i think the setup.py is expecting onnxruntime\backend to be in your current working directory.
so you can try cd to the build directory where onnxruntime\backend exists
and call python d:\onnxruntime\setup.py install

Hi George, @jywu-msft Thanks for your quick reply. I found that the compilation mode in the documentation only supports cpu mode. Acutally, I need a gpu mode (onnxruntime-gpu) to support online inference. I tried a different way to install onnxruntime-gpu. but it still can not work. Is there another way to install onnxruntime-gpu in windows?

body:
If you specify '--use_cuda' as a build parameter it will build the gpu package. 

You may also need to specify the cuda_home and cudnn_home paths via either the command line or environment variables.

Thanks for all your help! I build the source code using gpu mode. but there are still some errors. onnxruntime-cpu is easy to follow and helpful for me. I think it is too time consuming for me to set up the enviroment of **onnxruntime-gpu**. I decided to give up temporarily. If there is a gpu based docker image, it will be easier for beginners and users.

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/11796873/70876225-bf95c900-1ff3-11ea-81b1-c80af807206e.png)
There are dockerfiles available here to create images for various build flavors - https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/tree/master/dockerfiles
